    ) VALUES (1375617, 'Calcitriol', 'Butalbital', 'Moderate', 'Coadministration with CYP450 inducers such as rifampin, isoniazid, barbiturates, and certain anticonvulsants may decrease the pharmacologic effects of vitamin D analogs. These agents are thought to induce the hepatic conversion of vitamin D to inactive metabolites and have been shown to reduce circulating levels of active vitamin D, sometimes accompanied by reduced serum calcium and increased parathyroid hormone levels. Patients on long-term anticonvulsant therapy have occasionally developed osteomalacia, presumably due to interference with vitamin D and calcium metabolism. There have also been isolated reports of patients who responded poorly to vitamin D supplements during treatment with phenytoin and/or primidone.', NULL, 'Patients receiving vitamin D analogs with CYP450 inducers should be monitored for potentially reduced vitamin D effects.', NULL, 'Patients receiving vitamin D analogs with CYP450 inducers should be monitored for potentially reduced vitamin D effects. Dosage adjustments may be necessary.', 'Metabolism', NULL, NULL, 'Moderate', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', 1767317475);
